Overview

Section 1. Statistical Test

1.1 Which statistical test did you use to analyze the NYC subway data? Did you use a one-tail or a two-tail P value? What is the null hypothesis? What is your p-critical value?

I used in my analysis the method Mann-Whitney - Wilcoxon rank-sum test as presented during the training and Welch Two Sample t-test . I decide use these methods because looks a great starting point to determine the null hypothesis using two samples. Based on the desciption, I used this test to be applied for two variables: rain and fog.

First I execute the test using fog:

(Null Hypotheses - H0) - There is no ridership difference between fog and no fog.

(Alternative Hypotethes - H1) - There is ridership difference between fog and no fog.

with_fog <- subset(ny, fog == 1)
with_fog <- with_fog[,"ENTRIESn_hourly"]
with_fog_mean <- mean(with_fog)

without_fog <- subset(ny, fog == 0)
without_fog <- without_fog[,"ENTRIESn_hourly"]
without_fog_mean <- mean(without_fog)

t.test(without_fog, with_fog, var.equal = F)

with_rain <- subset(ny, rain == 1)

1.2 Why is this statistical test applicable to the dataset? In particular, consider the assumptions that the test is making about the distribution of ridership in the two samples.

The non-parametric test Mann-Whitney does not assume any particular distribution and the data set showed to be non-normal. The distribution of the number of entries is statistically different between rainy and non rainy but not different between foggy and no foggy

1.3 What results did you get from this statistical test? These should include the following numerical values: p-values, as well as the means for each of the two samples under test.

The statistic test demonstrated that are a difference of entries between rainy and non rainy days. Its not completely conclusive, because it may have other factor that impact how many people use the subway.

1.4 What is the significance and interpretation of these results?

At a first look, we can identify the difference of ridership during rainy and non rainy days.

Section 2. Linear Regression

2.1 What approach did you use to compute the coefficients theta and produce prediction for ENTRIESn_hourly in your regression model:

I used Gradient descent (as implemented in exercise 3.5) firstly using Numpy. After, I used as reference an R implementation of Gradient Descent.

table <- aggregate(ENTRIESn_hourly ~ hour + rain + precipi + meantempi, data=ny,mean)

x <- table[, c("meantempi", "hour")]
y <- matrix(as.numeric(table$ENTRIESn_hourly), ncol=1) 

num.iterations <- 75

# Function to standardize input values
zscore <- function(x, mean.val=NA) {
  if(is.matrix(x)) return(apply(x, 2, zscore, mean.val=mean.val))
  if(is.data.frame(x)) return(data.frame(apply(x, 2, zscore, mean.val=mean.val)))
  if(is.na(mean.val)) mean.val <- mean(x)
  sd.val <- sd(x)
  if(all(sd.val == 0)) return(x) # if all the values are the same
  (x - mean.val) / sd.val 
}

# Standardize the features
x.scaled <- zscore(x)

# Gradient descent function
grad <- function(x, y, theta) {
  gradient <- (1 / nrow(y)) * (t(x) %*% ((x %*% t(theta)) - y))
  return(t(gradient))
}

gradient.descent <- function(x, y, alpha=0.1, num.iterations=500, threshold=1e-5, output.path=FALSE) {
  # Add x_0 = 1 as the first column
  m <- nrow(x)  
  c0 <- rep(1, times = m)
  x <- cbind(c0, x)
  x <- apply(x, 2, as.numeric)
  
  num.features <- ncol(x)
  
  # Initialize the parameters
  theta <- matrix(rep(0, num.features), nrow=1)
  
  # Look at the values over each iteration
  theta.path <- theta
  for (i in 1:num.iterations) {
    
    theta <- theta - alpha * grad(x, y, theta)
    
    if(all(is.na(theta))) break
    theta.path <- rbind(theta.path, theta)
    #print(theta.path)
    if(i > 2) if(all(abs(theta - theta.path[i-1,]) < threshold)) break 
  }
  
  if(output.path) 
    return(theta.path) 
  else 
    return(theta.path[nrow(theta.path),])
}

scaled.theta <- gradient.descent(x=x.scaled, y=y, num.iterations=num.iterations, output.path=TRUE)

summary(lm(y ~ meantempi, data=x.scaled))
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ meantempi, data = x.scaled)
## 
## Residuals:

## Coefficients:

## (Intercept)  1250.12      32.61  38.337   <2e-16 ***
## meantempi     -26.40      32.62  -0.809    0.418    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1344 on 1696 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.0003861,  Adjusted R-squared:  -0.0002033 
## F-statistic: 0.655 on 1 and 1696 DF,  p-value: 0.4184
dt <- data.frame(table)
ggplot(dt, aes(x = dt$meantempi, y=dt$ENTRIESn_hourly))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()+
  ylab("Entries by Hour")+
  xlab("Average tamperature (F)")

qplot(1:(nrow(scaled.theta)), scaled.theta[,1], geom=c("line"), xlab="iteration", ylab="theta_1")

qplot(1:(nrow(scaled.theta)), scaled.theta[,2], geom=c("line"), xlab="iteration", ylab="theta_2")

# Look at output for various different alpha values
vary.alpha <- lapply(c(1e-9, 1e-7, 1e-3, 0.1), function(alpha) gradient.descent(x=x, y=y, alpha=alpha, num.iterations=num.iterations, output.path=TRUE))

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
for (j in 1:4) {
  plot(vary.alpha[[j]][,2], ylab="area (alpha=1e-9)", xlab="iteration", type="l")
}

Your reasons might be based on intuition. For example, response for fog might be: I decided to use fog because I thought that when it is very foggy outside people might decide to use the subway more often. Your reasons might also be based on data exploration and experimentation, for example: I used feature X because as soon as I included it in my model, it drastically improved my R2 value.

I choose these features beacause thinking as a human being, probably I would go by subway when its raining or the mean temperature is very high or very low. But, considering the location (NY), what I notice in the dataset is that there are no a significant increase of ridership between rain/no rain and fog/no fog. Also I didnt see significant increase based on the other features. Probably, independent of the weather conditions, people have to go around to labors, medics, universities, etc

Section 3. Visualization

Please include two visualizations that show the relationships between two or more variables in the NYC subway data.

The plot above show the mean Entries by Date. The color differs when it was raining or not. We can observe that during the rainy and clear days the average is almost the same.

The Histogram above shows the distribution of ridership splitted by rainy and clear days.

In the map above, we can observe the ridership distribution by station. The size represent average Entries by station, and we can see clearly that those stations located on Manhattan has more volume of ridership than others. It make sense, since the downtown has more stores, offices, companies, and the flow of people is higher.

Based on the graph, for a human being, its hard to notice a substatial difference between rainy and clear days.

Section 4. Conclusion

4.1 From your analysis and interpretation of the data, do more people ride the NYC subway when it is raining or when it is not raining?

From my analysis, I cant see a significant increase of ridership when its raining. Basically by the fact of the location, like New York, which is a dense region, and the faster way to get around certainly is the subway, many people use subway independently when its rainy or not. The average of ridership during the time frame remain almost the same, just with small spikes, which may be explained by other factor that is not included on the sample.

4.2 What analyses lead you to this conclusion?

Based on the dataset, the statistic methods used, plotting different correlation between variables, and a great feeling about how people need to get around every day. I dont know the NYC subway, but here in the South of Brazil, usually peoplo goes to work by bus or car. Those who goes every day by bus, during rainy day can choose other transportation. Many people leave the car in houses garage and pick up bus to get around to the city. During rainy days those people may choose by take a cab, but usually they will get bus.

In NYC I think that is quite different. As far I know about central area, is to much expensive ride a car and hard to find a place to park. Furthermore, I imagine the NYC subway is a high level service, with quality, fast and confort. So my conclusion is that indiferently when its rainy or not the NYC subwar still is the best choice for those who need to go work, medic, education, etc

Section 5. Reflection

5.1 Please discuss potential shortcomings of the methods of your analysis, including: Dataset, Analysis, such as the linear regression model or statistical test.

Analysis:

My formal graduation and expertise is Computer Science. Also, I like to analyze data trying to find insights and currently I work as a Data Architect within a project for a multinational big player computer company. I am not a statistician, and many statistics concepts need to be learned to understand and apply correctly the methods. So one potential shortcoming may be that I have applied incorrectly the presented statistics methods which may have led to make a wrong analysis. For that I will review all implementations and concepts.

Linear Regression is a common and very used method, but Gradient Descent is new to me and Ill review the steps and improve my implementation and analysis

Dataset:

Maybe, the dataset could include more variables that would help us to understand some variations on ridership such as:

  1. Price - The price may impact directly how people choose to go by subway, or choose other way like bus, cab, bike. One simple question would be: Do more people ride the subway when the price decrease?

  2. Snow - When its snowing may impact how many people goes by subway?

  3. Special events or date - Do more people get around during periods of time where has more cultural options like special shows, theater or sport events.
